    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-12-22T14:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-12-22T14:00:00-05:00" n="617"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d617">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 665.11251/37</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_PWH1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                    <placeName>
                        <hi rend="italic">London</hi>
                    </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-12-22T19:00:00+00:00">
                        <hi rend="italic">December 22, 1914, 7 p.m.</hi>
                    </date>
                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received December 23, 8 a.m.</hi>] </dateline>
                <p rend="center">[Telegram]</p>
                <p>1319. Your 776, December 18.<note n="1" xml:id="d617fn1">Not printed.</note>
                    <persName corresp="#p_GSE1">Sir Edward Grey</persName> informs me that his
                    understanding is that Italy does not prohibit export of cotton, unless it be
                    perhaps because of consignment to order, and that the Italian Government knows
                    that Great Britain will stop no ship because of cotton and no cargo of cotton.
                    When attention was called to the statement that American cotton was stopped
                    while <pb facs="0719" n="405" xml:id="pg_405"/> Egyptian was permitted to go, he
                    denied its accuracy, and said that he had had an Egyptian complaint that
                    Egyptian cotton was stopped and American was permitted to go, which also he
                    denied.</p>
                <closer>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Ambassador</hi>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
